-# Website Penetration Test Plan & Execution Guide
-
-**Target Application:** Premier Lumber Co. Website
-**Target URL:** `https://premierlumber.com` (Target Placeholder: `<TARGET>`)
-**Date:** 2026-02-17
-**Tester:** Authorized Security Tester
-
----
-
-## 1. Pre-Engagement Checklist
-
-Before starting any active testing, ensure the following are confirmed:
-
-- [ ] **Authorization:** Written permission (this document + user request) to test the target.
-- [ ] **Scope Defined:**
-  - **In-Scope:** `https://premierlumber.com` and subdomains.
-  - **Exclusions:** Hosting provider infrastructure (Hostinger panels), external services (Google Maps, Analytics APIs), DoS attacks.
-- [ ] **Backup:** Recent backup of the website and database (if applicable) created.
-- [ ] **Test Window:** Unlimited (Async/Offline testing allowed).
-- [ ] **Rate Limits:** Max 2 requests/second to prevent IP blocking by Hostinger.
-- [ ] **Emergency Contact:** User/Owner email available in case of outage.
-- [ ] **Toolchain:** All required GitHub tools installed and updated.
-- [ ] **Credentials:** N/A (Project is primarily public/anonymous).
-- [ ] **Legal:** "Safe Harbor" clause - testing is conducted for defensive purposes.
-- [ ] **Success Criteria:** Zero Critical/High vulnerabilities remaining; all findings documented with remediation.
-
----
-
-## 2. Threat Model Snapshot
-
-### Assets & Data
-
-1.  **Customer PII:** Names, emails, phone numbers, addresses (via Quote Form).
-2.  **Reputation:** Brand trust, SEO ranking.
-3.  **Server Resources:** Bandwidth, Compute (Hostinger shared hosting).
-4.  **Source Code:** Intellectual property (Proprietary designs/logic).
-5.  **Email Deliverability:** Domain reputation (preventing spam relays).
-6.  **Internal Photos/Content:** Unreleased marketing assets.
-7.  **Analytics Data:** User behavior patterns.
-8.  **Configuration Secrets:** API keys (if any), `.env` files.
-
-### Trust Boundaries
-
-- **Public Internet** vs **Web Server (`public_html`)**
-- **Web Server** vs **PHP Backend (`mail.php`)**
-- **Client Browser** vs **External APIs (Google Maps)**
-
-### Top 8 Abuse Cases (Ranked)
-
-1.  **Form Spamming:** Attacker floods `mail.php` to exhaust email quotas or harass staff.
-2.  **XSS on Admin/User:** Injecting scripts to steal sessions (if auth exists) or deface site.
-3.  **Data Exfiltration:** Accessing sensitive files (`.env`, `.git`) left in public root.
-4.  **Business Logic Bypass:** Submitting quotes without required fields or with fake data.
-5.  **Malicious File Upload:** Uploading a web shell via a hidden upload endpoint (if exists).
-6.  **Supply Chain Attack:** Compromising a 3rd party npm package to inject crypto miners.
-7.  **Internal Info Leak:** Discovering `/photo-review` or other dev-only pages.
-8.  **Header Injection:** Manipulating email headers in the contact form to spoof senders.
-
----
-
-## 3. Test Plan & Phases
-
-### Phase A: Passive Reconnaissance
-
-_Goal: Map the attack surface without triggering alarms._
-
-- **DNS & Subdomains:** Check for forgotten dev subdomains.
-- **Certificate Transparency:** Look for historic domains.
-- **Technology Fingerprinting:** Identify server version, headers.
-- **Google Dorking:** Find exposed files.
-
-**Commands (Safe Mode):**
-
-```bash
-# 1. HTTP Probing (Title/Tech stack)
-httpx -u <TARGET> -title -tech-detect -status-code
-
-# 2. Certificate Recon
-curl -s "https://crt.sh/?q=%25.premierlumber.com&output=json" | jq .
-
-# 3. Google Dorks (Manual)
-# site:premierlumber.com filetype:php
-# site:premierlumber.com "index of"
-# site:premierlumber.com inurl:admin
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** `dev.premierlumber.com` resolves, "Index of /" exposed.
-
-### Phase B: Configuration, Headers & TLS
-
-_Goal: Verify transport security and browser protections._
-
-- **SSL/TLS:** Check for weak ciphers, old protocols (TLS 1.0/1.1).
-- **Security Headers:** HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options.
-- **Cookie Flags:** Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite.
-- **CORS:** Wildcard policies.
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-# 1. TLS/SSL Scan (Fast)
-testssl.sh --fast --quiet <TARGET>
-
-# 2. Header Analysis
-curl -I <TARGET>
-
-# 3. CORS Check (Manual)
-curl -I -H "Origin: https://evil.com" <TARGET>/mail.php
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`, Missing HSTS, TLS 1.0 enabled.
-
-### Phase C: Authentication & Session Management
-
-_Goal: Ensure identity mechanisms are robust (mostly N/A for this brochure site)._
-
-- **Cookie Inspection:** Check for sensitive data in cookies.
-- **Session Fixation:** (If auth existed).
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-# Check cookies
-curl -v <TARGET> 2>&1 | grep "Set-Cookie"
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** `PHPSESSID` without `Secure` flag.
-
-### Phase D: Authorization & Access Control
-
-_Goal: Find hidden or unprotected routes._
-
-- **Forced Browsing:** Check for common files (`README.md`, `.git`).
-- **Route Fuzzing:** Guess commonly unused routes.
-- **IDOR:** (N/A unless user IDs exist).
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-# 1. Check for sensitive files (Manual lists preferred over brute force)
-curl -I <TARGET>/.env
-curl -I <TARGET>/.git/HEAD
-curl -I <TARGET>/composer.json
-curl -I <TARGET>/package.json
-curl -I <TARGET>/README.md
-
-# 2. Check for known internal route
-curl -I <TARGET>/photo-review
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** `200 OK` on `.env` or `/photo-review`.
-
-### Phase E: Input Handling & Injection (Focus: `mail.php`)
-
-_Goal: Test the contact form and backend handling safely._
-
-- **XSS (Reflected):** Does the form echo input back?
-- **Header Injection:** Can we add `Bcc:`?
-- **Logic Bypass:** Skip the timestamp check.
-- **JSON Injection:** Malformed JSON.
-- **Null Byte Injection (2025 Trend):** Test for CVE-2025-1220 bypasses.
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-# 1. Valid Request (Baseline)
-curl -X POST <TARGET>/mail.php \
-  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-  -d '{"name":"Test","email":"test@example.com","phone":"123","message":"Hello","_ts":1710000000}'
-
-# 2. Logic Bypass: Omit Timestamp (Should fail or be blocked, but might pass)
-curl -X POST <TARGET>/mail.php \
-  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-  -d '{"name":"Bot","email":"bot@example.com","phone":"000"}'
-
-# 3. XSS Probe (Safe Payload)
-curl -X POST <TARGET>/mail.php \
-  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-  -d '{"name":"<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>","email":"test@example.com"}'
-
-# 4. Header Injection Probe
-curl -X POST <TARGET>/mail.php \
-  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-  -d '{"email":"test@example.com\r\nBcc: evil@example.com", "name":"Inj"}'
-
-# 5. Null Byte Injection (CVE-2025-1220 Probe)
-curl -X POST <TARGET>/mail.php \
-  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
-  -d '{"email":"test@example.com%00.evil.com", "name":"NullByte"}'
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** Form returns success without `_ts`, XSS payload echoed in response JSON.
-
-### Phase F: File Uploads
-
-_Goal: Verify no unauthorized uploads._
-
-- **Scan:** Check if any `/upload` endpoints exist.
-
-**Evidence:** Review code or `dir` scan. Usage of `mail.php` suggests no file upload support.
-
-### Phase G: Dependency & Supply Chain
-
-_Goal: Identify vulnerable libraries._
-
-- **NPM Audit:** Check `package.json`.
-- **Outdated JS:** jQuery/Bootstrap versions.
-- **Vite/React Exposure:** Check for leaked `VITE_` env vars in production build.
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-npm audit
-# OR
-trivy fs .
-
-# Check for leaked env vars in JS bundles
-grep -r "VITE_" dist/
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** Critical CVEs in `react-router-dom` or `vite`.
-
-### Phase H: SAST & Secrets
-
-_Goal: Find bugs in source code._
-
-- **Secrets:** API keys, passwords in code.
-- **Bad Patterns:** unsafe `innerHTML`, `eval()`.
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-# 1. Secrets Scan
-gitleaks detect --source . -v
-
-# 2. Static Analysis
-semgrep scan --config=auto .
-```
-
-**Bad Signals:** AWS keys found, `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` usage.
-
-### Phase I: Infrastructure
-
-_Goal: Host level checks._
-
-- **Server Version:** Apache/Nginx exposed?
-- **Open Ports:** (Only 80/443 expected).
-- **Shared Hosting Isolation:** Test for symlink attacks (if shell access exists).
-
-**Commands:**
-
-```bash
-curl -I <TARGET>
-# If SSH access available:
-# ls -la ../
-```
-
----
-
-## 4. Pre-Identified Findings (Bonus)
-
-_These findings were discovered during the initial source code review phase._
-
-### High Severity
-
-- **F01: Content Security Policy (CSP) Weakness**
-  - **Description:** `.htaccess` defines `script-src 'unsafe-inline'`. This allows inline scripts to run, negating protection against XSS.
-  - **Fix:** Use Nonces or Hashes for inline scripts.
-- **F02: Wildcard CORS on Backend**
-  - **Description:** `public/mail.php` sets `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *`. Any malicious website can send POST requests to your email trigger.
-  - **Fix:** Set specific domain: `header("Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://premierlumber.com");`
-
-### Medium Severity
-
-- **F03: Anti-Bot Timestamp Bypass**
-  - **Description:** `mail.php` only checks timestamp _if_ `_ts` is present in the payload. Bots can check by simply omitting the field.
-  - **Fix:** Make `_ts` mandatory or default to 0 if missing.
-- **F04: Exposed Internal Route**
-  - **Description:** `/photo-review` is a public route in `App.tsx` and likely accessible to anyone who guesses the URL.
-  - **Fix:** Remove the route or add Basic Auth protection.
-- **F05: Missing Rate Limit on Client**
-  - **Description:** No Captcha or client-side rate limit visual.
-  - **Fix:** Add Turnstile or ReCaptcha.
-
-### Low Severity
-
-- **F06: Information Disclosure (Headers)**
-  - **Description:** `X-Powered-By` or Server headers might be present (verify with scan).
-- **F07: Email Spoofing Risk**
-  - **Description:** `mail.php` uses user-supplied email in `Reply-To` without strict validation (though verify `filter_var` usage).
-- **F08: Legacy Comments/Code**
-  - **Description:** "TODO" comments in `mail.php` about SMS gateways.
-- **F09: README.md Disclosure**
-  - **Description:** `README.md` might be accessible at web root.
-- **F10: Source Map Exposure**
-  - **Description:** `.map` files might be generated in production build (verify `dist/` contents).
-
----
-
-## 5. GitHub Toolchain Install
-
-Quick install commands for a Windows (likely utilizing WSL) or Linux environment:
-
-```bash
-# 1. OWASP ZAP (Docker)
-docker pull softwaresecurityproject/zap-stable
-
-# 2. testssl.sh
-git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/drwetter/testssl.sh.git
-
-# 3. ProjectDiscovery Tools (Go required)
-go install -v github.com/projectdiscovery/httpx/cmd/httpx@latest
-go install -v github.com/projectdiscovery/katana/cmd/katana@latest
-
-# 4. Semgrep
-python3 -m pip install semgrep
-
-# 5. Gitleaks
-# (Download binary from GitHub releases or:)
-brew install gitleaks
-
-# 6. Trivy
-browse install aquasecurity/trivy/trivy
-```
